  "prompt": "What is the basis of reservation in India?",
  "response": "The reservation system in India is designed to improve the social and educational status of historically disadvantaged communities. It provides them with a certain percentage of seats in educational institutions, government jobs, and even in legislatures. The basis of reservation in India primarily includes:\n\n1. **Caste**: The system predominantly operates on caste lines. Scheduled Castes (SC), Scheduled Tribes (ST), and Other Backward Classes (OBC) are the primary beneficiaries of the reservation policies. These categories were identified based on their historical social and educational disadvantages.\n\n2. **Economic Status**: More recently, economic criteria have also been introduced as a basis for reservation, with the implementation of the Economically Weaker Sections (EWS) quota. This is aimed at individuals who are not covered under existing reservation schemes but belong to economically disadvantaged backgrounds.\n\n3. **Gender**: Gender-based reservation is also employed, notably in educational institutions and within certain caste-based reservations, to increase the representation of women.\n\n4. **Geographical and Other Factors**: In some cases, reservations are provided for people from specific regions or areas that are considered backward, or for various other minor categories, including physically handicapped individuals.\n\nReservation aims to promote equality by providing opportunities to those who have been historically marginalized, thereby serving as a tool for social justice and inclusion. However, the system has been a subject of debate and controversy regarding its implementation, effectiveness, and impact on society.",
